OL,3,CNew mothers 'should do two hours of
OL,4,Cmoderate to vigorous exercise every
OL,5,Cweek'
OL,7,F"Postpartum women and people who
OL,8,Ffollow this guideline for physical
OL,9,Factivity, sedentary behaviour and
OL,10,Fsleep will likely experience a large
OL,11,Fimprovement in their psychological
OL,12,Fwellbeing (ie reduction in the
OL,13,Fprevalence of depression, symptoms of
OL,14,Fdepression and anxiety); pelvic floor
OL,15,Fhealth (ie reduction in the risk of
OL,16,Furinary incontinence); musculoskeletal
OL,17,Fhealth (ie reduction in low back and
OL,18,Fpelvic girdle pain symptoms and
OL,19,Fseverity); cardiometabolic health (ie
OL,20,Fimprovement in weight, body mass index
OL,21,Fand blood lipids); and a reduction in
OL,22,Ffatigue, while not experiencing
OL,23,Fadverse effects (eg reduced breastmilk
OL,24,Fsupply or injury)."
